name: Calcium and Phosphate
question1: Storage and Distribution of calcium within the body, Functions of Calcium (7),  Regulation Calcium (3),
contents:
Body stored -

  • IN ECF 900 mg <--//--> ICF 9,000mg <-- // --> Accretion, exchange and reabsorption 600mg BONE - 1Kg
  • Input -
  • absorption 400mg
  • secretion 300mg
  • Average daily turnover:
  • 1,000mg (1g) - GI tract
  • Filtered and reabsorbed in the kidneys
  • Filtered - 10,000mg
  • Reabsorbed - 9,900mg
  • Urine 100mg


Distribution of Calcium within the body :

  • Skeleton - 99%
  • Intracellular - 1%
  • Extracellular - 0.1%. (2.2 - 2.5 mmol/l)
  • ionised Ca2+ (45%) - 1.15 - 1.13 mmol/l)
  • increased by PTH/VitaminD. (increases absorption of Ca2+ from intestine and kidneys)
  • bound to :
  • plasma proteins (45%)
  • ions eg phosphate, lactate, HCO3- (10%)


Function of Calcium

  1. Bone growth and remodelling
  2. Secretion
  3. Muscle contraction
  4. Blood clotting
  5. Co-enzyme
  6. Stabilization of membrane potentials
  7. Second messenger/stimulus response coupling


Regulation of plasma calcium depends principally up on the actions of (1) PTH (2) vitamin D and to a lesser extend (3) calcitonin

(1) PTH secretion is directly stimulated by a fall in calcium and acts to elevate it in several ways, thereby, providing negative feedback control.

It has four (4) main actions.

  • Stimulation of calcium release from bones
  • Stimulation of the rate of calcium reabsorption from the renal tubules
  • Increased urinary phosphate excretion.
  • Acceleration of the rate at which vitamin D is converted to its active form (1,25 dihydrocholecalciferol) within the kidneys.

(2) Vitamin D is:

  • a fat-soluble vitamin which is derived either from dietary sources, or by UV radiation from sunlight stimulating the production of Vitamin D3 (cholecalciferol) in the skin
  • in the circulation cholecalciferol is converted to 25-hydroxycholecalciferol in the liver.
  • 25-hydroxycholecalciferol --> 1,25 dihydrocholecalciferol in the kidneys.
  • The formation of this active metabolite is stimulated by PTH, low plasma Ca2+ and low plasma phosphate levels.

(3) Calcitonin :

  • is secreted by C cells of the thyroid gland.
  • acts on bone to reduce the rate of calcium release - and therefore tends to lower Ca2+
question2: Discuss source/anatomy of PTH, Actions of PTH
contents2:
Source

  • 4 glands on upper and lower poles of each lobe of the thyroid gland
  • Supernumerary glands not uncommon (source of PTH excess?)
  • 30-50 mg weight
  • Chief cells and oxyphill cells
  • Supplied by blood from thyroid arteries (thyroid surgery)
  • The cleavage of the NH2 from PTH-1-84 produces the active PTH hormone.


Physiology/Actions

Actions on Ca2+/ PO4 and Vitamin D

  • PTH secreted in response to ↓Ca2+. (??Release stimulated by extracellular unbound ionised calcium)
  • ↑Ca2+ and ↓PO4 reabsorption in kidney (DCT)
  • ↑ phosphate excretion
  • ↑ 1α-hydroxylation of 25OH-Vit D3. (PCT)
  • ↑ PTH → activation of OSTEOCLASTS ± osteoblasts
  • → Binds to PTH type 1 receptor (PTH1-Rc) on osteoblasts:
  • = change in activity of osteoclast-differentiating factor / ?M-CSF / RANKL = osteoclast activation via RANK receptor
  • = increased bone resorption

put another way

  • Osteoblast stimulates the differentiation of osteoclasts by the production of RANK ligand. 
  • This activates the RANK receptor on the osteoclast precursor and
  • via activation of nuclear kappa beta stimulates gene transcription and differentiation of osteoclasts. 
  • OPG binding to RANK inhibits differentiation




Presentation of hypercalcemia: ↑ Ca2+: stones (renal), bones (pain) and moans (depression) ↑ BP (check Ca2+ in all with HTN)


Parathyroid hormone

  • Release stimulated by extracellular unbound ionised calcium
  • Increases clearance of phosphate = indirectly increases mobilisation of calcium from bone
  • Acts on G-protein coupled receptors
  • Binds to PTH type 1 receptor (PTH1-Rc) on osteoblasts = change in activity of osteoclast-differentiating factor / RANKL = osteoclast activation via RANK receptor
question3: Functions of phosphate [ H2PO4- and HPO42-] (6) Hypophosphataemia causes and clinical manifestations
contents3:
• Input 1-1.5g/day - 1400mg/day
  • absorption of 0.9g/day - 900mg/day (double the amount of Ca2+)
  • secretion 0.2 g/day


Distribution of Phosphate

  • Skeleton - 90%
  • Intracellular - 5%
  • Extracellular - <0.03% (0.8 - 1.2 mmol/l)
  • 50% free
  • Controlled by kidneys + effects of PTH (increase PTH causes PO4 excretion) and FGF23
  • 50% bound

Functions

  • Element in:
  • (1) High energy compounds e.g. ATP
  • (2) Second messengers e.g. cAMP
  • Constituent of:
  • (3) DNA/RNA, phospholipid membranes,
  • (4) Bone
  • (5) Intracellular anion (in cells)
  • (6) Phosphorylation (activation) of enzymes



Phosphate


  • Hypophosphataemia
  • May be caused by:
  • Hyperparathyroidism
  • Osteomalacia
  • Acute alkalosis
  • Haemodialysis
  • Refeeding syndrome
  • Clinical manifestations:
  • Muscle weakness + respiratory failure, rhabdomyolysis
  • Peripheral neuropathy
  • Seizures, coma
  • Haemolysis + impaired platelet function
contents4:
Mg2+ is the 2nd most important IC cation after K+

Found in

  • Bone
  • Soft tissue
  • Muscle


ICF

Function -

  • Activates many enzyme systems including those involved with energy metabolism.
  • It has an essential role in the production of ATP - which is fully functional only when chelated to Mg2+
  • Synthesis of RNA/DNA and Proteins
  • Essential regulator of Ca2_ and the IC actions of Ca2+
